Content: Let’s bring some data to the ongoing debate around SEO vs GEO vs AEO vs OMG. 

In Fractl & Search Engine Land's research, which I presented at SMX Advanced, the overlap between traditional SEO winners and AI-cited brands was surprisingly low. Only 7.2% of domains appeared in both Google AI Overviews and leading LLM results. 

That suggests this isn’t just “SEO 2.0.” 

Especially considering some teams focus solely on technical SEO, while others view SEO as content marketing and earned media strategies that engineer brand authority and visibility across channels. 

In my experience, GEO is not about gaming models. It’s about understanding how authority, reputation, and distribution affect whether a brand is even eligible to be surfaced across generative engines like ChatGPT, Gemini, Claude. These systems draw from a mix of web signals, training data, publisher partnerships, forums like Reddit, video ecosystems like YouTube, and other distributed credibility layers that extend well beyond traditional SEO levers. 

This is why we should reflect on the terminologies we use to reference visibility in these new consumer search platforms. 

Research:
https://lnkd.in/ey4Xn4_E

That said, the acronym debate continues, and no clear winner has emerged across the two studies we've published in the past four months. In Nov 26, we found: 

AEO drove higher LinkedIn engagement (8.1 vs 5.5)
GEO led in awareness (84% vs 61%)
GEO led in usage (42% vs 14%)
GEO led in quarter-over-quarter search interest growth (121% vs 56%)

Research:
https://lnkd.in/e3EbhY54

We expanded this analysis in Jan 2026 to examine terminology adoption among trusted SEO industry leaders. Alarmingly, fewer than 1/3 have maintained consistent usage and sentiment around AI-related SEO terminology over the past year!

While 65% of posts using AEO carried positive sentiment, 83% of GEO posts did. GEO was also the only term where sentiment among thought leaders closely mirrored broader market sentiment, and that alignment often predicts long-term adoption. 

Still, perspective matters: 43% of SEO thought leaders include “SEO” in their LinkedIn headline, vs just 21% referencing “AI" and 3% referencing “GEO.”

Research: https://lnkd.in/eWm2aWJ9

IMHO, backed by data, the strategies that drive brand visibility in generative engines and search engines overlap, but the systems are not identical. Nevertheless, our fundamentals still win: actionable, data-backed content, trusted subject matter experts, and authoritative earned media builds lasting brand authority and engagement across platforms. 

At brass tacks, this isn’t about one acronym replacing another! Generative engines represent a new consumer search platform, and the best SEOs have the skills to engineer cross-channel brand visibility far beyond traditional SERPs.

