Over the past year, I've been endlessly entertained reading SEO industry banter, as thought leaders raced to own the latest keywords rapidly redefining consumer search:

"It's called GEO!" 
"Well, we use AEO!...I mean, AISEO!" 
"Guys...it all relies on effective SEO..."

I felt like it was time we get to the hard numbers behind the industry echo chamber, so I could align my own team with what's gaining traction.

Over the last few weeks, my agency, Fractl, partnered with Search Engine Land to survey marketers, scrape thousands of social conversations, and analyze job boards to understand which terms are actually gaining traction.

Our key findings:

💡 Only 14% of our survey respondents used SEO as the label for AI-driven brand discovery, despite believing SEO still powers it.

📈 Marketers overwhelmingly recognize GEO (84%), AEO (61%), and AISEO (60%). 

📊 BUT, when forced to *choose the one label they use* to describe AI-driven brand visibility, usage consolidated heavily around GEO (42%), with AISEO (16%) and AEO (14%) well behind, while all other acronyms faded into niche awareness.

💓 On LinkedIn: SEO with AI baked in sparks the highest positive sentiment, while acronyms like AISEO, AEO, LLMO over-index in engagement.

🤯 Hiring managers favor the most intuitive label: AISO now appears in 11,001 U.S. job listings... more than SEO, GEO, AEO, and LLMO combined.

So what does this all mean? 

Marketers aren't ditching SEO. They're stacking new mental models on top of it. 

Or, as Danny Goodwin put it: "Don't call it confusion — call it evolution."

